s with the Artist models of the late 1970s, some of these guitars were equipped with trisound switches, and some models (MC 400 and MC 500) were equipped with active electronics.\nBULLET::::- ST – Studio series 1977–82 offset double cutaway ranging from bolt on to fixed and through necks with pairs of V2 distortion humbuckers. 24 frets and 25.5\" scale.\nBULLET::::- CN – Concert range 1977–79 like a bolt on neck Artist with slightly offset cutaways.\nBULLET::::- IC – Iceman a radical shape endorsed and used by Paul Stanley, Various pickup combinations.\nBULLET::::- BL – Blazer series 1980–82 – fixed bridge strat-like with maple necks and mahogany or ash bodies sporting 3 single coil pickups (Super 6 or BL) or 2 Super 70 humbuckers.\nBULLET::::- ARC-100/300 (Retro Series)\nBULLET::::- ARX-100/300 (Retro Series)\nBULLET::::- AR-100/200 (black vintage top)\nBULLET::::- V Series – Flying V's – discontinued\nBULLET::::- Ibanez Artcore Series – Ibanez's full and semi-hollow guitar line, with some models discontinued since their debut in 2002.\nBULLET::::- Ibanez Jet King 2 and Jet King 1 – A modern remake of the Ibanez Rhythm maker, vintage looking and sounding guitars.\nBULLET::::- Radius series – discontinued, a modified version is now taken over by the Joe Satriani signature series which features a multi-radius neck.\nBULLET::::- EX Series – Manufactured in Korea and Japan (rare).\nBULLET::::- PL – Pro Line series\nBULLET::::- RR – Rocket Roll\nBULLET::::- DT – Destroyer\nBULLET::::- IC – Iceman\nBULLET::::- Talman Series – discontinued\nBULLET::::- CN Concert Series – This was a short lived series produced in 1978 then discontinued soon afterwards. It features an asymmetric double cutaway body with two humbuckers, a hard tail bridge and a bolt on neck. The top end model (the CN250) was one of the earliest guitars to feature \"half vine\" fingerboard inlays.\nBULLET::::- Power II series (540PII) - extended length lower cutaway, wide (1 3/4\")nut,available in H-H or H-S