{"id": "14926", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=14926", "title": "List of Italian dishes", "text": "List of Italian dishes\n\nThis is a list of Italian dishes and foods. Italian cuisine has developed through centuries of social and political changes, with roots as far back as the 4th century BC. Italian cuisine has its origins in Etruscan, ancient Greek, and ancient Roman cuisines.\nSignificant changes occurred with the discovery of the New World and the introduction of potatoes, tomatoes, bell peppers and maize, now central to the cuisine but not introduced in quantity until the 18th century. The cuisine of Italy is noted for its regional diversity, abundance of difference in taste, and is known to be one of the most popular in the world, with influences abroad.\n\nPizza and spaghetti, both associated with the Neapolitan traditions of cookery, are especially popular abroad, but the varying geographical conditions of the twenty regions of Italy, together with the strength of local traditions, afford a wide range of dishes.\n\nThe cuisine of Italy has many unique dishes and foods.\n\nBULLET::::- Acquacotta – an Italian soup that was originally a peasant food. Historically, its primary ingredients were water, stale bread, onion, tomato and olive oil, along with various vegetables and leftover foods that may have been available.\nBULLET::::- Agghiotta di lumache (Sicilian snail soup)\nBULLET::::- Agliata\nBULLET::::- Agrodolce\nBULLET::::- Bagna càuda\nBULLET::::- Capra e fagioli\nBULLET::::- Cioppino broth based seafood stew, served with grilled bread\nBULLET::::- Garmugia\nBULLET::::- Ginestrata\nBULLET::::- Grine sauce\nBULLET::::- Maccu\nBULLET::::- Sugo al Pomodoro\nBULLET::::- Minestra di ceci\nBULLET::::- Minestra di pasta con pesce\nBULLET::::- Minestrone\nBULLET::::- Pasta e fagioli\nBULLET::::- Ragù alla bolognese\nBULLET::::- Ragù alla napoletana\nBULLET::::- Ragù alla salsiccia\nBULLET::::- Ragù – a meat-based sauce commonly served with pasta\nBULLET::::- Risi e bisi\nBULLET::::- Sciusceddu\nBULLET::::- Stracciatella\nBULLET::::- Boreto\nBULLET::::- Fonduta\nBULLET::::- Minestra di fagioli\nBULLET::::- Pesto\n\nBULLET::::- Bari\nBULLET::::- Bozza pratese\nBULLET::::- Casatiello\nBULLET::::- Ciabatta – an Italian white bread made from wheat flour, water, salt, olive oil, and yeast, created in 1982 by a baker in Adria, Veneto, Italy, in response to popularity of French baguettes\nBULLET::::- Ciaccino\nBULLET::::- Ciriola – typical bread of Rome\nBULLET::::- Colomba Pasquale\nBULLET::::- Coppia Ferrarese\nBULLET::::- Cornetto\nBULLET::::- Crescentina\nBULLET::::- Crocchè\nBULLET::::- Farinata\nBULLET::::- Ficattola\nBULLET::::- Focaccia\nBULLET::::- Fragguno\nBULLET::::- Grissini torinesi\nBULLET::::- Michetta – typical bread of Milan\nBULLET::::- Moddizzosu\nBULLET::::- Muffuletta\nBULLET::::- Neccio\nBULLET::::- Pandoro\nBULLET::::- Pane carasau\nBULLET::::- Pane casareccio\nBULLET::::- Pane di Altamura\nBULLET::::- Pane di Genzano (Lazio)\nBULLET::::- Pane pugliese\nBULLET::::- Pane di Laterza\nBULLET::::- Pane rustico – traditional crusty peasant bread\nBULLET::::- Pane toscano – without salt\nBULLET::::- Panelle di ceci\nBULLET::::- Panettone\nBULLET::::- Panino\nBULLET::::- Penia\nBULLET::::- Piadina\nBULLET::::- Pita – typical bread of Catanzaro\nBULLET::::- Rosetta – typical bread of Rome\nBULLET::::- Schiacciata\nBULLET::::- Taralli\nBULLET::::- Testarolo\nBULLET::::- Tigella\nBULLET::::- Tortano\nBULLET::::- Ai frutti di mare – an Italian seafood pizza that may be served with scampi, mussels or squid\nBULLET::::- Calzone – folded over dough usually filled with ricotta and other ingredients\nBULLET::::- Focaccia al rosmarino – a pizza based on rosemary and olive oil, sometimes served with prosciutto, usually served as appetizer\nBULLET::::- Pizza ai funghi e salsiccia – pizza with mushroom and sausage or boscaiola, with mozzarella, mushrooms and sausages, with or without tomato\nBULLET::::- Pizza al taglio – (Italian for pizza by the slice — literally \"by the cut\") is a variety of pizza baked in large rectangular trays, and generally sold in rectangular or square slices by weight, with prices marked per kilogram or per 100 grams. This type of pizza was invented in Rome, Italy, and is common throughout Italy.\nBULLET::::- Pizza ai quattro formaggi – (four cheese pizza) with four different cheeses (sometimes melted together, sometimes in sectors), with (rossa, red) or without tomato sauce (bianca, white)\nBULLET::::- Pizza alla napoletana (or Neapolitan) – tomato, mozzarella and anchovy\nBULLET::::- Pizza capricciosa – with tomato, mozzarella, mushrooms, artichokes, black and green olives\nBULLET::::- Pizza Margherita – tomato and mozzarella\nBULLET::::- Pizza marinara – tomato, oregano and garlic\nBULLET::::- Pizza pugliese – tomato, mozzarella and onions\nBULLET::::- Pizza quattro stagioni (four seasons pizza) – based on tomato and divided in four sectors, one for each season:\nBULLET::::- Pizza romana (Roman pizza) – tomato, mozzarella, capers and anchovy\nBULLET::::- Pizza siciliana (Sicilian pizza) – tomato, mozzarella, capers, olive and anchovy\n\nBULLET::::- Agnolotti\nBULLET::::- Bavette, bigoli, bucatini\nBULLET::::- Cannelloni, crespelle\nBULLET::::- Capellini, cappelletti\nBULLET::::- Chitarra\nBULLET::::- Conchiglie\nBULLET::::- Ditalini\nBULLET::::- Eliche\nBULLET::::- Farfalle, festoni, fettuccine, filatieddi, fusilli\nBULLET::::- Garganelli\nBULLET::::- Gnocchi\nBULLET::::- Gnocchi di semolino – dumplings made with semolina flour\nBULLET::::- Lasagna, linguine, lumache (snails), lasagnette\nBULLET::::- Maccheroni (macaroni), malloreddus (Sardinian pasta), maltagliati, marille, marrubini\nBULLET::::- Offelle, orecchiette\nBULLET::::- Orzo\nBULLET::::- Paccheri, paglia e fieno, pansotti, panzarotti, pappardelle, penne, perciatelli, pici, pinzillacchere, pizzoccheri,\nBULLET::::- Ravioli, rigatoni\nBULLET::::- Spaghetti, spaghetti alla chitarra, str