ia, is named after him. A crater on the planet Mercury, Calvino, and a main belt asteroid, \"22370 Italocalvino\", are also named after him. \"Salt Hill Journal\" and University of Louisville award annually the Italo Calvino Prize \"for a work of fiction written in the fabulist experimental style of Italo Calvino\".\n\nBULLET::::- 1946 – L'Unità Prize (shared with Marcello Venturi) for the short story, \"Minefield\" (\"Campo di mine\")\nBULLET::::- 1947 – Riccione Prize for \"The Path to the Nest of Spiders\"\nBULLET::::- 1952 – Saint-Vincent Prize\nBULLET::::- 1957 – Viareggio Prize for \"The Baron in the Trees\"\nBULLET::::- 1959 – Bagutta Prize\nBULLET::::- 1960 – Salento Prize for \"Our Ancestors\"\nBULLET::::- 1963 – International Charles Veillon Prize for \"The Watcher\"\nBULLET::::- 1970 – Asti Prize\nBULLET::::- 1972 – Feltrinelli Prize for \"Invisible Cities\"\nBULLET::::- 1976 – Austrian State Prize for European Literature\nBULLET::::- 1981 – Legion of Honour\nBULLET::::- 1982 – World Fantasy Award – Life Achievement\n\nBULLET::::- Calvino, Italo. \"Adam, One Afternoon\" (trans. Archibald Colquhoun, Peggy Wright). London: Minerva, 1992.\nBULLET::::- —. \"The Castle of Crossed Destinies\" (trans. William Weaver). London: Secker & Warburg, 1977\nBULLET::::- —. \"Cosmicomics\" (trans. William Weaver). London: Picador, 1993.\nBULLET::::- —. \"The Crow Comes Last\" (\"Ultimo viene il corvo\"). Turin: Einaudi, 1949.\nBULLET::::- —. \"Difficult Loves. Smog. A Plunge into Real Estate\" (trans. William Weaver, Donald Selwyn Carne-Ross). London: Picador, 1985.\nBULLET::::- —. \"Hermit in Paris\" (trans. Martin McLaughlin). London: Jonathan Cape, 2003.\nBULLET::::- —. \"If on a winter's night a traveller\" (trans. William Weaver). London: Vintage, 1998.\nBULLET::::- —. \"Invisible Cities\" (trans. William Weaver). London: Secker & Warburg, 1974.\nBULLET::::- —. \"Italian Fables\" (trans. Louis Brigante). New York: Collier, 1961. (50 tales)\nBULLET::::- —. \"Italian F